mainMeasure: Retail Prices Index calculated using the Jevons formula (RPIJ)
description:
Consumer price indices are important indicators of how the UK economy is performing.

The indices are used in many ways by the government, businesses, and society in general. They can affect interest rates, tax allowances, wages, state benefits, pensions, maintenance, contracts and many other payments. They also show the impact of inflation on family budgets and affect the value of the pound in your pocket.

breadcrumb.title: Economy
breadcrumb.summary: An economy or economic system consists of the production, distribution, consumption and trade of limited goods and services by different agents in a given geographical location. The economic agents can be individuals, businesses, organisations, or governments.

breadcrumb.title: Inflation and price indices
breadcrumb.summary: Inflation measures the rate of increase in prices for goods and services using price indices. The rate of inflation used in the UK government’s inflation target is measured using the Consumer Prices Index (CPI). One way to understand the CPI is to think of a very large shopping basket containing a large selection of the goods and services bought by households, the CPI estimates changes to the total cost of this basket.
